,"2  Chinese: non-standard romanization of the Chinese surname 鄭,  see  Cheng   (3).","3  Chinese: non-standard romanization of the Chinese surname 戴,  see  Tai   (1)."],"variants":[{"name":"Tee","meanings":["English: variant of   Tye  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 鄭, see   Zheng   1.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 池, possibly based on its Hokkien or Teochew pronunciation, see   Chi   1."]},{"name":"Cheng","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ming, Kin, Wing, Ping, Wai, Chi, Wei, Yan, Hong, Kam, Ying, Chin.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 程, meaning ‘measurement’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Cheng (程), the name of a state (probably located in Henan province) granted to Xiu Fu by King Xuan of Zhou (reigned 827–782  BC ). (ii) from the placename Cheng (程), the name of a fief (located in Shaanxi province) granted to descendants of the Xun (荀) family in the state of Jin (located mainly in present-day Shanxi province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 成, meaning ‘accomplish’ or ‘become’ in Chinese: (i) from the placename Cheng (郕), the name of a fief (located in present-day Henan province) granted to Shu Wu, son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (1152–1056  BC ). His descendants adopted the name of the fiefdom as their surname, and simplified it to 成 by dropping the second component of the Chinese character 郕. (ii) from the placename Cheng (郕), the name of a fief (located in present-day Shandong province) granted to Ji Dai by King Wu of Zhou (<i>c.</i> 1087–1043  BC ). His descendants simplified the name of the fiefdom 郕 to 成 and adopted it as their surname. (iii) from Cheng Hu (成虎), style name of the son of Ruo Ao, who was a high official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). His descendants inherited 成, part of his name, as their surname. (iv) for some families, the surname also originated from the Tu Ge tribe of the Huns, resident in northwestern China. (vi) for other families, the surname also originated in the indigenous tribes in ancient southern China."]},{"name":"Tai","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Kam, Ming, Cheung, Chi Sing, Han, Hong, Hsing, Man, On, Pin, Ping.  Korean Hak, Nam, Woon, Cho, Chong, Chung, Heeyoung, Kok, Min, Pang, Tam, Wook.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 邰: (i) from the placename Tai (邰), the name of a fief (located in Wugong in Shaanxi province) granted to Hou Ji, an official during the reign of the legendary Emperor Yao (<i>c.</i> 24th century  BC ). (ii) complicated form of the Chinese character Tai (台), the name of a place (located in Shandong province) in the state of Lu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) adopted as a surname by the Da Li Ji (大利稽) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":28,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":101,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Knight John Tey was born about 1354, in Marks Tey, Essex, England. He married Mrs. John Tey before 1379, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Rayleigh, Essex, England."},"et":{"about 1354–":"umbes 1354–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1379–1400":"1379–1400","1354–Male":"1354–Surnud","before 1379":"enne 1379","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1354":"1354","about 1354":"umbes 1354","1382":"1382","Rayleigh, Essex, England":"Rayleigh, Essex, England","Marks Tey, Essex, England":"Marks Tey, Essex, England","Europe":"Europe","Marks Tey, Lexdon, Essex, England":"Marks Tey, Essex, England"},"fi":{"about 1354–":"noin 1354–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1379–1400":"1379–1400","1354–Male":"1354–Kuollut","before 1379":"ennen vuotta 1379","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1354":"1354","about 1354":"noin 1354","1382":"1382","Rayleigh, Essex, England":"Rayleigh, Essex, England","Marks Tey, Essex, England":"Marks Tey, Essex, England","Europe":"Europe","Marks Tey, Lexdon, Essex, England":"Marks Tey, Essex, England"},"fr":{"about 1354–":"environ 1354–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1379–1400":"1379–1400","1354–Male":"1354–Décédé","before 1379":"avant 1379","1379":"1379","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1354":"1354","about 1354":"environ 1354","1382":"1382","Rayleigh, Essex, England":"Rayleigh, Essex, Angleterre","Marks Tey, Essex, England":"Marks Tey, Essex, Angleterre","Europe":"Europe","Marks Tey, Lexdon, Essex, England":"Marks Tey, Essex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sir Knight John Tey est né environ 1354, à Marks Tey, Essex, Angleterre. Il a épousé Mrs. John Tey avant 1379, à Europe